# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: nuklear-ui
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:nuklear-ui/font-rasterization] The simplest form of rasterization is simple line-drawing with no anti-aliasing of any kind.
[src:nuklear-ui/font-rasterization] In Microsoft's terminology, this is called *bi-level* (and more popularly "black and white") rendering because no intermediate shades (of gray) are used to draw the glyphs.
[src:nuklear-ui/font-rasterization] (In fact, any two colors can be used as foreground and background.) This form of rendering is also called aliased or "jagged".
[src:nuklear-ui/font-rasterization] This is the fastest rendering method in the sense that it requires the least computational effort.
[src:nuklear-ui/font-rasterization] However, it has the disadvantage that rendered glyphs may lose definition and become hard to recognize at small sizes.
[src:nuklear-ui/font-rasterization] Therefore, many font data files (such as TrueType) contain hints that help the rasterizer decide where to render pixels for particularly troublesome areas in the glyphs, or sets of hand-tweaked bitmaps to use at specific pixel sizes.
[src:nuklear-ui/font-rasterization] As a prototypical example, all versions of Microsoft Windows prior to Windows 95 (e.g.
[src:nuklear-ui/font-rasterization] Windows 3.1) only provided this type of built-in rasterizer.
[src:nuklear-ui/font-rasterization] Rasterization with anti-aliasing with hinting.
[src:nuklear-ui/font-rasterization] Here pixels are forced to fall into integral pixel coordinates whenever possible.
[src:nuklear-ui/font-rasterization] A more complicated approach is to use standard anti-aliasing techniques from computer graphics.
[src:nuklear-ui/font-rasterization] This can be thought of as determining, for each pixel at the edges of the character, how much of that pixel the character occupies, and drawing that pixel with that degree of opacity.
[src:nuklear-ui/font-rasterization] For example, when drawing a black (000000) letter on a white (FFFFFF) background, if a pixel ideally should be half filled (perhaps by a diagonal line from corner to corner) it is drawn 50% gray (BCBCBC).
[src:nuklear-ui/font-rasterization] Over-simple application of this procedure can produce blurry glyphs.
[src:nuklear-ui/font-rasterization] For example, if the letter includes a vertical line that should be one pixel wide but falls exactly between two pixels, it appears on screen as a two-pixel-wide gray line.
[src:nuklear-ui/font-rasterization] This blurriness trades clarity for accuracy.
[src:nuklear-ui/font-rasterization] However, modern systems often force lines to fall within integral pixel coordinates, which makes glyphs look sharper, but also makes lines slightly wider or thinner than they would have looked on a printed sheet of paper.
[src:nuklear-ui/font-rasterization] Most computer displays have pixels made up of multiple subpixels (typically one each for red, green, and blue, which are combined to produce the full range of colours).
[src:nuklear-ui/font-rasterization] In some cases, particularly with flat panel displays, it is possible to exploit this by rendering at the subpixel resolution rather than using whole pixels, which can increase the effective resolution of the screen.
[src:nuklear-ui/font-rasterization] This is generally known as subpixel rendering.
[src:nuklear-ui/font-rasterization] One proprietary implementation of subpixel rendering is Microsoft's ClearType.
[src:nuklear-ui/font-rasterization] In modern operating systems, rasterization is normally provided by a shared library common to many applications.
[src:nuklear-ui/font-rasterization] Such a shared library may be built into the operating system or the desktop environment, or may be added later.
[src:nuklear-ui/font-rasterization] In principle, each application may use a different font rasterization library, but in practice most systems attempt to standardize on a single library.
[src:nuklear-ui/font-rasterization] Microsoft Windows has supported subpixel rendering since Windows XP.
[src:nuklear-ui/font-rasterization] This has changed with Direct2D/DirectWrite shipping on Windows 7 and Windows Vista platform update, allowing subpixel text positioning to 1/16 pixel sizes.
[src:nuklear-ui/font-rasterization] The result is that the on-screen display looks extremely similar to printed output, but can occasionally be difficult to read at smaller point sizes.
[src:nuklear-ui/font-rasterization] The Quartz renderer has, since macOS Mojave, removed subpixel rendering, relying purely on greyscale anti-aliasing instead.
[src:nuklear-ui/font-rasterization] This change is acceptable to HiDPI "retina" screens, but makes text on external monitors harder to read.
[src:nuklear-ui/font-rasterization] Most other systems use the FreeType library, which depending on the settings, can fall anywhere between Microsoft's and Apple's implementations; it supports hinting and anti-aliasing, and optionally performs subpixel rendering and positioning.
[src:nuklear-ui/font-rasterization] FreeType also offers some features not present in either implementation such as color-balanced subpixel rendering and gamma correction.
[src:nuklear-ui/font-rasterization] Applications may also bring their own font rendering solutions.
[src:nuklear-ui/font-rasterization] Graphics frameworks like Skia Graphics Engine (used by Google Chrome) occasionally use their own font renderer.
[src:nuklear-ui/font-rasterization] Video games and other 3D applications may also need faster, GPU-based renderers such as various SDF-based renderers and "Slug".
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] A **framebuffer** (**frame buffer**, or sometimes **framestore**) is a portion of random-access memory (RAM) containing a bitmap that drives a video display.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] It is a memory buffer containing data representing all the pixels in a complete video frame.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] Modern video cards contain framebuffer circuitry in their cores.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] This circuitry helps convert an in-memory bitmap into a video signal that can be displayed on a computer monitor.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] In computing, a **screen buffer** is a part of computer memory used by a computer application for the representation of the content to be shown on the computer display.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] The screen buffer may also be called the **video buffer**, the **regeneration buffer**, or **regen buffer** for short.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] The phrase "screen buffer” refers to a logical function, while *video memory* refers to a hardware storage location.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] In particular, the screen buffer may be placed in the main RAM, the video memory, or some other hardware location.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] To reduce latency and avoid screen tearing, multiple frames can be buffered, and this technique is called multiple buffering.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] When this is so, at any time, only one frame would be visible, and the others would not be.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] The currently invisible frames are located in the **off-screen buffer**.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] The information in the buffer typically consists of color values for every pixel to be shown on the display.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] Color values are commonly stored in 1-bit binary (monochrome), 4-bit palettized, 8-bit palettized, 16-bit high color and 24-bit true color formats.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] An additional alpha channel is sometimes used to retain information about pixel transparency.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] The total amount of memory required for the framebuffer depends on the resolution of the output signal, and on the color depth or palette size.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] Computer researchers had long discussed the theoretical advantages of a framebuffer but were unable to produce a machine with sufficient memory at an economically practicable cost.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] In 1947, the Manchester Baby computer used a Williams tube, later the Williams-Kilburn tube, to store 1024 bits on a cathode-ray tube (CRT) memory and displayed on a second CRT.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] Other research labs were exploring these techniques with MIT Lincoln Laboratory achieving a 4096 display in 1950.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] A color-scanned display was implemented in the late 1960s, called the Brookhaven RAster Display (BRAD), which used a drum memory and a television monitor.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] Michael Noll of Bell Telephone Laboratories, Inc. implemented a scanned display with a frame buffer, using magnetic-core memory.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] A year or so later, the Bell Labs system was expanded to display an image with a color depth of three bits on a standard color TV monitor.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] The vector graphics used in the computer had to be converted for the scanned graphics of a TV display.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] This led to the development of the SuperPaint system by Richard Shoup at Xerox PARC in 1972.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] Shoup was able to use the SuperPaint framebuffer to create an early digital video-capture system.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] By synchronizing the output signal to the input signal, Shoup was able to overwrite each pixel of data as it shifted in.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] Shoup also experimented with modifying the output signal using color tables.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] These color tables allowed the SuperPaint system to produce a wide variety of colors outside the range of the limited 8-bit data it contained.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] This scheme would later become commonplace in computer framebuffers.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] In 1974, Evans & Sutherland released the first commercial framebuffer, the Picture System, costing about $15,000.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] It was capable of producing resolutions of up to 512 by 512 pixels in 8-bit grayscale, and became a boon for graphics researchers who did not have the resources to build their own framebuffer.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] The New York Institute of Technology would later create the first 24-bit color system using three of the Evans & Sutherland framebuffers.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] Each framebuffer was connected to an RGB color output (one for red, one for green and one for blue), with a Digital Equipment Corporation PDP 11/04 minicomputer controlling the three devices as one.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] In 1975, the UK company Quantel produced the first commercial full-color broadcast framebuffer, the Quantel DFS 3000.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] It was first used in TV coverage of the 1976 Montreal Olympics to generate a picture-in-picture inset of the Olympic flaming torch while the rest of the picture featured the runner entering the stadium.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] The rapid improvement of integrated-circuit technology made it possible for many of the home computers of the late 1970s to contain low-color-depth framebuffers.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] Today, nearly all computers with graphical capabilities utilize a framebuffer for generating the video signal.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] Amiga computers, created in the 1980s, featured special design attention to graphics performance and included a unique Hold-And-Modify framebuffer capable of displaying 4096 colors.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] Framebuffers also became popular in high-end workstations and arcade system boards throughout the 1980s.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] SGI, Sun Microsystems, HP, DEC and IBM all released framebuffers for their workstation computers in this period.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] These framebuffers were usually of a much higher quality than could be found in most home computers, and were regularly used in television, printing, computer modeling and 3D graphics.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] Framebuffers were also used by Sega for its high-end arcade boards, which were also of a higher quality than on home computers.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] Framebuffers used in personal and home computing often had sets of defined *modes* under which the framebuffer can operate.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] These modes reconfigure the hardware to output different resolutions, color depths, memory layouts and refresh rate timings.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] In the world of Unix machines and operating systems, such conveniences were usually eschewed in favor of directly manipulating the hardware settings.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] This manipulation was far more flexible in that any resolution, color depth and refresh rate was attainable – limited only by the memory available to the framebuffer.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] An unfortunate side-effect of this method was that the display device could be driven beyond its capabilities.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] In some cases, this resulted in hardware damage to the display.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] More commonly, it simply produced garbled and unusable output.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] Modern CRT monitors fix this problem through the introduction of protection circuitry.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] When the display mode is changed, the monitor attempts to obtain a signal lock on the new refresh frequency.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] If the monitor is unable to obtain a signal lock or if the signal is outside the range of its design limitations, the monitor will ignore the framebuffer signal and possibly present the user with an error message.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] LCD monitors tend to contain similar protection circuitry, but for different reasons.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] Since the LCD must digitally sample the display signal (thereby emulating an electron beam), any signal that is out of range cannot be physically displayed on the monitor.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] Framebuffers have traditionally supported a wide variety of color modes.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] Due to the expense of memory, most early framebuffers used 1-bit (2 colors per pixel), 2-bit (4 colors), 4-bit (16 colors) or 8-bit (256 colors) color depths.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] The problem with such small color depths is that a full range of colors cannot be produced.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] The solution to this problem was indexed color, which adds a lookup table to the framebuffer.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] Each color stored in framebuffer memory acts as a color index.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] The lookup table serves as a palette with a limited number of different colors, while the rest is used as an index table.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] In some designs, it was also possible to write data to the lookup table (or switch between existing palettes) on the fly, allowing dividing the picture into horizontal bars with their own palette and thus rendering an image that had a far wider palette.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] For example, viewing an outdoor shot photograph, the picture could be divided into four bars: the top one with emphasis on sky tones, the next with foliage tones, the next with skin and clothing tones, and the bottom one with ground colors.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] This required each palette to have overlapping colors, but, carefully done, allowed great flexibility.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] While framebuffers are commonly accessed via a memory mapping directly to the CPU memory space, this is not the only method by which they may be accessed.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] Framebuffers have varied widely in the methods used to access memory.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] The framebuffer organization may be packed pixel or planar.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] The framebuffer may be all points addressable or have restrictions on how it can be updated.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] Video cards always have a certain amount of RAM.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] A small portion of this RAM is where the bitmap of image data is "buffered" for display.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] The term *frame buffer* is thus often used interchangeably when referring to this RAM.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] The CPU sends image updates to the video card.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] The video processor on the card forms a picture of the screen image and stores it in the frame buffer as a large bitmap in RAM.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] The bitmap in RAM is used by the card to continually refresh the screen image.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] Many systems attempt to emulate the function of a framebuffer device, often for reasons of compatibility.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] The two most common virtual framebuffers are the Linux framebuffer device (fbdev) and the X Virtual Framebuffer (Xvfb).
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] Xvfb was added to the X Window System distribution to provide a method for running X without a graphical framebuffer.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] The Linux framebuffer device was developed to abstract the physical method for accessing the underlying framebuffer into a guaranteed memory map that is easy for programs to access.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] This increases portability, as programs are not required to deal with systems that have disjointed memory maps or require bank switching.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] A frame buffer may be designed with enough memory to store two frames' worth of video data.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] In a technique known generally as double buffering or more specifically as page flipping, the framebuffer uses half of its memory to display the current frame.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] While that memory is being displayed, the other half of the memory is filled with data for the next frame.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] Once the secondary buffer is filled, the framebuffer is instructed to display the secondary buffer instead.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] The primary buffer becomes the secondary buffer, and the secondary buffer becomes the primary.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] This switch is often done after the vertical blanking interval to avoid screen tearing where half the old frame and half the new frame is shown together.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] Page flipping has become a standard technique used by PC game programmers.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] As the demand for better graphics increased, hardware manufacturers created a way to decrease the amount of CPU time required to fill the framebuffer.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] This is commonly called *graphics acceleration*.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] Common graphics drawing commands (many of them geometric) are sent to the graphics accelerator in their raw form.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] The accelerator then rasterizes the results of the command to the framebuffer.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] This method frees the CPU to do other work.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] Early accelerators focused on improving the performance of 2D GUI systems.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] While retaining these 2D capabilities, most modern accelerators focus on producing 3D imagery in real time.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] A common design uses a graphics library such as OpenGL or Direct3D, which interfaces with the graphics driver to translate received commands to instructions for the accelerator's graphics processing unit (GPU).
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] The GPU uses those instructions to compute the rasterized results and the results are bit blitted to the framebuffer.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] The framebuffer's signal is then produced in combination with built-in video overlay devices (usually used to produce the mouse cursor without modifying the framebuffer's data) and any final special effects that are produced by modifying the output signal.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] An example of such final special effects was the spatial anti-aliasing technique used by the 3dfx Voodoo cards.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] These cards add a slight blur to the output signal that makes aliasing of the rasterized graphics much less obvious.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] At one time there were many manufacturers of graphics accelerators, including: 3dfx Interactive; ATI; Hercules; Trident; Nvidia; Radius; S3 Graphics; SiS and Silicon Graphics.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] As of 2015 the market for graphics accelerators for x86-based systems is dominated by Nvidia (acquired 3dfx in 2002), AMD (who acquired ATI in 2006), and Intel.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] With a framebuffer, the electron beam (if the display technology uses one) is commanded to perform a raster scan, the way a television renders a broadcast signal.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] The color information for each point thus displayed on the screen is pulled directly from the framebuffer during the scan, creating a set of discrete picture elements, i.e., pixels.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] Framebuffers differ significantly from the vector displays that were common prior to the advent of raster graphics (and, consequently, to the concept of a framebuffer).
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] With a vector display, only the vertices of the graphics primitives are stored.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] The electron beam of the output display is then commanded to move from vertex to vertex, tracing a line across the area between these points.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] Likewise, framebuffers differ from the technology used in early text mode displays, where a buffer holds codes for characters, not individual pixels.
[src:nuklear-ui/framebuffer] The video display device performs the same raster scan as with a framebuffer but generates the pixels of each character in the buffer as it directs the beam.
[src:nuklear-ui/graphics-library] A **graphics library** or **graphics API** is a program library designed to aid in rendering computer graphics to a monitor.
[src:nuklear-ui/graphics-library] This typically involves providing optimized versions of functions that handle common rendering tasks.
[src:nuklear-ui/graphics-library] This can be done purely in software and running on the CPU, common in embedded systems, or being hardware accelerated by a GPU, more common in PCs.
[src:nuklear-ui/graphics-library] By employing these functions, a program can assemble an image to be output to a monitor.
[src:nuklear-ui/graphics-library] This relieves the programmer of the task of creating and optimizing these functions, and allows them to focus on building the graphics program.
[src:nuklear-ui/graphics-library] Graphics libraries are mainly used in video games and simulations.
[src:nuklear-ui/graphics-library] The use of graphics libraries in connection with video production systems, such as Pixar RenderMan, is not covered here.
[src:nuklear-ui/graphics-library] Some APIs use Graphics Library (GL) in their name, notably OpenGL and WebGL.
[src:nuklear-ui/graphics-library] Dedicated graphics processors use RAM allocated directly to the graphics processor rather than the computer’s main system memory.
[src:nuklear-ui/graphics-library] This RAM is usually specifically selected with the expected sequential load of the graphics card in mind (see GDDR).
[src:nuklear-ui/graphics-library] Sometimes systems with dedicated discrete graphics processors were called “DIS” systems in contrast to “UMA” systems.
[src:nuklear-ui/graphics-library] Technologies such as 3dfx's Scan-Line Interleave, Nvidia's SLI and NVLink, and AMD's CrossFire allow multiple graphics processors to simultaneously display images on one screen, increasing the computational power available for graphics processing.
[src:nuklear-ui/graphics-library] However, these technologies are becoming increasingly rare; most games do not utilize all the capabilities of multiple graphics processors since most users cannot afford them.
[src:nuklear-ui/graphics-library] Today, laptops and mini-PCs require powerful integrated graphics.
[src:nuklear-ui/graphics-library] In many cases, quality integrated graphics can replace a discrete graphics card, enhancing laptop portability and mini-PC compactness while maintaining performance.
[src:nuklear-ui/graphics-library] Integrated graphics processors (IGPU), integrated graphics, shared graphics solutions, integrated graphics processors (IGP), or unified memory architectures (UMA) use part of the computer’s RAM rather than dedicated graphics memory.
[src:nuklear-ui/graphics-library] IGP may be integrated into the motherboard as part of its northbridge chipset or on a single chip (integrated circuit) with the central processor (e.g., AMD APU or Intel HD Graphics).
[src:nuklear-ui/graphics-library] On some motherboards, AMD’s IGP may use sideport dedicated memory: a separate fixed block of high-performance memory allocated for use by the graphics processor.
[src:nuklear-ui/graphics-library] As of early 2007, computers with integrated graphics accounted for about 90% of all PC shipments.
[src:nuklear-ui/graphics-library] They are less expensive to implement than dedicated graphics processing but generally less powerful.
[src:nuklear-ui/graphics-library] Historically, integrated processing was considered unsuitable for 3D games or graphics-intensive applications but could run less resource-demanding programs like Adobe Flash.
[src:nuklear-ui/graphics-library] Examples of such IGPs include offerings from SiS and VIA around 2004.
[src:nuklear-ui/graphics-library] However, modern integrated graphics processors such as AMD Accelerated Processing Unit and Intel Graphics Technology (HD, UHD, Iris, Iris Pro, Iris Plus, and Xe-LP) can handle 2D graphics or undemanding 3D graphics.
[src:nuklear-ui/graphics-library] In systems with a “unified memory architecture” (UMA), including modern AMD processors with integrated graphics, modern Intel processors with integrated graphics, Apple processors, PS5, and Xbox Series (among others), the CPU cores and GPU unit share the same pool of RAM and memory address space.
[src:nuklear-ui/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] without the use of extensive indirection – thus***immediate***– to retained resources.
[src:nuklear-ui/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] It does not preclude the use of double-buffering.
[src:nuklear-ui/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] Retained mode is an alternative approach.
[src:nuklear-ui/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] Historically, retained mode has been the dominant style in GUI libraries; however, both can coexist in the same library and are not necessarily exclusive in practice.
[src:nuklear-ui/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] In immediate mode, the scene (complete object model of the rendering primitives) is retained in the memory space of the client, instead of the graphics library.
[src:nuklear-ui/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] This implies that in an immediate mode application, the lists of graphical objects to be rendered are kept by the client and are not saved by the graphics library API.
[src:nuklear-ui/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] The application must re-issue all drawing commands required to describe the entire scene each time a new frame is required, regardless of actual changes.
[src:nuklear-ui/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] This method provides on the one hand a maximum of control and flexibility to the application program, but on the other hand it also generates continuous work load on the CPU.
[src:nuklear-ui/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] Examples of immediate mode rendering systems include Direct2D, OpenGL and Quartz.
[src:nuklear-ui/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] There are some immediate mode GUIs that are particularly suitable when used in conjunction with immediate mode rendering systems.
[src:nuklear-ui/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] Primitive vertex attribute data may be inserted frame by frame into a command buffer by a rendering API.
[src:nuklear-ui/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] This involves significant bandwidth and processor time (especially if the graphics processing unit is on a separate bus), but may be advantageous for data generated dynamically by the CPU.
[src:nuklear-ui/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] It is less common since the advent of increasingly versatile shaders, with which a graphics processing unit may generate increasingly complex effects without the need for CPU intervention.
[src:nuklear-ui/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] Graphical user interfaces traditionally use retained mode-style API design, but immediate mode GUIs instead use an immediate mode-style API design, in which user code directly specifies the GUI elements to draw in the user input loop.
[src:nuklear-ui/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] For example, rather than having a CreateButton() function that a user would call once to instantiate a button, an immediate-mode GUI API may have a DoButton() function which should be called whenever the button should be on screen.
[src:nuklear-ui/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] The technique was developed by Casey Muratori in 2002.
[src:nuklear-ui/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] Prominent implementations include Omar Cornut's Dear ImGui in C++, Nic Barker's Clay in C and Micha Mettke's Nuklear in C.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] While vector hardware has largely disappeared in favor of raster-based monitors and printers, vector data and software continue to be widely used, especially when a high degree of geometric precision is required, and when complex information can be decomposed into simple geometric primitives.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] Thus, it is the preferred model for domains such as engineering, architecture, surveying, 3D rendering, and typography, but is entirely inappropriate for applications such as photography and remote sensing, where raster is more effective and efficient.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] Some application domains, such as geographic information systems (GIS) and graphic design, use both vector and raster graphics at times, depending on purpose.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] Vector graphics are based on the mathematics of analytic or coordinate geometry, and is not related to other mathematical uses of the term vector.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] This can lead to some confusion in disciplines in which both meanings are used.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] The logical data model of vector graphics is based on the mathematics of coordinate geometry, in which shapes are defined as a set of points in a two- or three-dimensional cartesian coordinate system, as *p* = (*x, y*) or *p* = (*x, y, z*).
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] Because almost all shapes consist of an infinite number of points, the vector model defines a limited set of geometric primitives that can be specified using a finite sample of salient points called vertices.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] For example, a square can be unambiguously defined by the locations of three of its four corners, from which the software can interpolate the connecting boundary lines and the interior space.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] Because it is a regular shape, a square could also be defined by the location of one corner, a size (width=height), and a rotation angle.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] In many vector datasets, each shape can be combined with a set of properties.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] The most common are visual characteristics, such as color, line weight, or dash pattern.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] In systems in which shapes represent real-world features, such as GIS and BIM, a variety of attributes of each represented feature can be stored, such as name, age, size, and so on.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] In some Vector data, especially in GIS, information about topological relationships between objects may be represented in the data model, such as tracking the connections between road segments in a transport network.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] If a dataset stored in one vector file format is converted to another file format that supports all the primitive objects used in that particular image, then the conversion can be lossless.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] Vector-based devices, such as the vector CRT and the pen plotter, directly control a drawing mechanism to produce geometric shapes.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] Since vector display devices can define a line by dealing with just two points (that is, the coordinates of each end of the line), the device can reduce the total amount of data it must deal with by organizing the image in terms of pairs of points.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] Vector graphic displays were first used in 1958 by the US SAGE air defense system.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] Vector graphics systems were retired from the U.S. en route air traffic control in 1999.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] Vector graphics were also used on the TX-2 at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology Lincoln Laboratory by computer graphics pioneer Ivan Sutherland to run his program Sketchpad in 1963.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] Subsequent vector graphics systems, most of which iterated through dynamically modifiable stored lists of drawing instructions, include the IBM 2250, Imlac PDS-1, and DEC GT40.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] There was a video game console that used vector graphics called Vectrex as well as various arcade games like *Asteroids*, *Space Wars*, *Tempest* and many cinematronics titles such as *Rip Off*, and *Tail Gunner* using vector monitors.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] Storage scope displays, such as the Tektronix 4014, could display vector images but not modify them without first erasing the display.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] However, these were never as widely used as the raster-based scanning displays used for television, and had largely disappeared by the mid-1980s except for specialized applications.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] Plotters used in technical drawing still draw vectors directly to paper by moving a pen as directed through the two-dimensional space of the paper.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] However, as with monitors, these have largely been replaced by the wide-format printer that prints a raster image (which may be rendered from vector data).
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] Because this model is useful in a variety of application domains, many different software programs have been created for drawing, manipulating, and visualizing vector graphics.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] While these are all based on the same basic vector data model, they can interpret and structure shapes very differently, using very different file formats.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] Vector graphics are commonly found today in the SVG, WMF, EPS, PDF, CDR or AI types of graphic file formats, and are intrinsically different from the more common raster graphics file formats such as JPEG, PNG, APNG, GIF, WebP, BMP and MPEG4.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] The World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) standard for vector graphics is Scalable Vector Graphics (SVG).
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] The standard is complex and has been relatively slow to be established at least in part owing to commercial interests.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] Many web browsers now have some support for rendering SVG data but full implementations of the standard are still comparatively rare.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] In recent years, SVG has become a significant format that is completely independent of the resolution of the rendering device, typically a printer or display monitor.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] SVG files are essentially printable text that describes both straight and curved paths, as well as other attributes.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] Wikipedia prefers SVG for images such as simple maps, line illustrations, coats of arms, and flags, which generally are not like photographs or other continuous-tone images.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] Rendering SVG requires conversion to a raster format at a resolution appropriate for the current task.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] SVG is also a format for animated graphics.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] There is also a version of SVG for mobile phones called SVGT (SVG Tiny version).
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] These images can count links and also exploit anti-aliasing.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] They can also be displayed as wallpaper.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] CAD software uses its own vector data formats, usually proprietary formats created by software vendors, such as Autodesk's DWG and public exchange formats such as DXF.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] Modern displays and printers are raster devices; vector formats have to be converted to a raster format (bitmaps – pixel arrays) before they can be rendered (displayed or printed).
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] The size of the bitmap/raster-format file generated by the conversion will depend on the resolution required, but the size of the vector file generating the bitmap/raster file will always remain the same.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] Thus, it is easy to convert from a vector file to a range of bitmap/raster file formats but it is much more difficult to go in the opposite direction, especially if subsequent editing of the vector picture is required.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] It might be an advantage to save an image created from a vector source file as a bitmap/raster format, because different systems have different (and incompatible) vector formats, and some might not support vector graphics at all.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] However, once a file is converted from the vector format, it is likely to be bigger, and it loses the advantage of scalability without loss of resolution.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] It will also no longer be possible to edit individual parts of the image as discrete objects.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] The file size of a vector graphic image depends on the number of graphic elements it contains; it is a list of descriptions.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] Vector art is ideal for printing since the art is made from a series of mathematical curves; it will print very crisply even when resized.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] For instance, one can print a vector logo on a small sheet of copy paper, and then enlarge the same vector logo to billboard size and keep the same crisp quality.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] A low-resolution raster graphic would blur or pixelate excessively if it were enlarged from business card size to billboard size.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] If we regard typographic characters as images, then the same considerations that we have made for graphics apply even to the composition of written text for printing (typesetting).
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] Older character sets were stored as bitmaps.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] Therefore, to achieve maximum print quality they had to be used at a given resolution only; these font formats are said to be non-scalable.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] High-quality typography is nowadays based on character drawings (fonts) which are typically stored as vector graphics, and as such are scalable to any size.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] Examples of these vector formats for characters are Postscript fonts and TrueType fonts.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] For example, consider a circle of radius *r*.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] Vector formats are not always appropriate in graphics work and also have numerous disadvantages.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] For example, devices such as cameras and scanners produce essentially continuous-tone raster graphics that are impractical to convert into vectors, and so for this type of work, an image editor will operate on the pixels rather than on drawing objects defined by mathematical expressions.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] Comprehensive graphics tools will combine images from vector and raster sources, and may provide editing tools for both, since some parts of an image could come from a camera source, and others could have been drawn using vector tools.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] Some authors have criticized the term *vector graphics* as being confusing.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] In particular, *vector graphics* does not simply refer to graphics described by Euclidean vectors.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] Some authors have proposed to use *object-oriented graphics* instead.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] However this term can also be confusing as it can be read as any kind of graphics implemented using object-oriented programming.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] Vector graphics editors typically allow translation, rotation, mirroring, stretching, skewing, affine transformations, changing of z-order (loosely, what's in front of what) and combination of primitives into more complex objects.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] More sophisticated transformations include set operations on closed shapes (union, difference, intersection, etc.).
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] In SVG, the composition operations are based on alpha composition.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] Vector graphics are ideal for simple or composite drawings that need to be device-independent, or do not need to achieve photo-realism.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] For example, the PostScript and PDF page description languages use a vector graphics model.
[src:nuklear-ui/vector-graphics] Many stock photo websites provide vectorized versions of hosted images, while specific repositories specialize in vector images given their growing popularity among graphic designers.
